Deployment Strategies
Deployment strategy means how a new version of an application is released to users.
Common Deployment Strategies
1. Recreate Deployment
Old version is stopped first, then the new version is deployed.
Advantage:
Simple to implement
Disadvantage:
Causes downtime
2. Rolling Deployment
New version is deployed gradually by replacing old servers one by one.
Advantage:
No downtime
Disadvantage:
Both old and new versions run together temporarily
3. Blue-Green Deployment
Two environments are maintained:
Blue = Current live version
Green = New version
Traffic is switched from Blue to Green after testing.
Advantage:
Very safe and quick rollback
Disadvantage:
Needs double infrastructure
4. Canary Deployment
New version is released to a small group of users first.
If successful, it is released to all users.
Advantage:
Low risk
Disadvantage:
Needs monitoring and traffic control
5. A/B Testing Deployment
Different versions are shown to different users to compare performance.
Advantage:
Useful for testing user behavior
Disadvantage:
More complex setup
